

<section>
  <title>Further exercises for \thesection</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Prove <xref ref="lin_of_coord_vectors">Lemma</xref>(b) in the case where <m>V</m> is two-dimensional,
        so that <m>\basis{B} = \bopen \ve{e}_1, \ve{e}_2\bclose</m>.
        Justify each step using the rules of a vector space.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="matrix_basis_exercise">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>\basis{B}</m> be the basis of <m>\Mat_{2,2}</m> given by
        <md>
          \mat{B}_1 = \cmatrix{1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  1},  \mat{B}_2 = \cmatrix{1 \amp  0 \\ 0 \amp  -1},  \mat{B}_3 = \cmatrix{1 \amp  1 \\ 1 \amp  1},  \mat{B}_4 = \cmatrix{0 \amp  1 \\ -1 \amp  0} \, .
        </md>
      </p>

      <p>
        Determine <m>[\mat{A}]_\basis{B}</m>, where
        <md>
          \mat{A} = \cmatrix{1 \amp  2 \\ 3 \amp  4} \, .
        </md>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        In <xref ref="dim_poly_at_2_ex">Exercise</xref>,
        you were asked to find a basis <m>\basis{B}</m> for the vector space
        <me>
          V := \{ p \in \Poly_2 : p(2) = 0 \}
        </me>.
      </p>

      <p>
        Consider <m>p(x) = x^2 + x - 6</m>.

        <ul>
          <li>
            <title>(a)</title>
            <p>
              Show that <m>p \in V</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <title>(b)</title>
            <p>
              Determine the coordinate vector of <m>p</m> with respect to your basis <m>\basis{B}</m>,
              i.e. determine <m>[p]_\basis{B}</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</section>

